  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. The primary global body responsible for setting standards and promoting the effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering is the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. The FATF is an intergovernmental organization established in 1989 by the G7 countries.\n\n### Key International Frameworks and Laws:\n\n1. **FATF Recommendations**:\n   - The FATF has developed a series of **40 Recommendations** (originally issued in 1990 and revised several times, most recently in 2012) that provide a comprehensive framework for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and the financing of proliferation of weapons of mass destruction.\n   - These recommendations are recognized as the global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): This was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering, specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): This convention requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to prevent it.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): This convention includes provisions for combating money laundering related to corruption.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has issued several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs)** to harmonize AML laws across member states. The most recent is the **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, which came into effect in December 2020 and strengthened measures against money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n4. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**:\n   - Both the IMF and the World Bank play significant roles in assisting countries in implementing AML/CFT measures through technical assistance and assessments of countries' compliance with FATF standards.\n\n5. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering, emphasizing the importance of **Know Your Customer (KYC)** procedures and due diligence.\n\n### Enforcement and Compliance:\n- **FATF Mutual Evaluations**: The FATF conducts mutual evaluations of its member countries to assess their compliance with the FATF Recommendations and to provide recommendations for improvement.\n- **Blacklists and Greylists**: The FATF maintains lists of countries that are non-cooperative in the fight against money laundering and terrorist financing, which can lead to international sanctions and restrictions.\n\n### Conclusion:\nInternational laws against money laundering are primarily driven by the FATF Recommendations and reinforced by various UN conventions and regional regulations like the EU directives. These frameworks provide a comprehensive approach to preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities globally. Compliance with these standards is essential for countries to avoid being blacklisted and to maintain their international financial relationships.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
